--- Prerequisite Definitions ---
**G**: Let $G$ be a group.

**integral basis**: A basis $(u_i)$ of the vector space $\mathbb{K}G$ is called an \underline{integral basis} if \begin{itemize} \item[(i)] each $u_i$ has the form $\sum_{x \in G} n_x x$ with rational integers $n_x$ and conversely \item[(ii)] every $x \in G$ has the form $\sum_i m_i u_i$ with integers $m_i$. \end{itemize}

---

\label{7.2}
Let $G = \left<x\right>$ be an infinite cyclic group, $n$ any positive integer and $u = 1-x$. Then $1, u, u^2, \ldots$ together with $u^n x^{-1}, u^n x^{-2}, \ldots$ form an integral basis of $\mathbb{K}G.$

--- Prerequisite Definitions ---
**integral basis**: A basis $(u_i)$ of the vector space $\mathbb{K}G$ is called an \underline{integral basis} if \begin{itemize} \item[(i)] each $u_i$ has the form $\sum_{x \in G} n_x x$ with rational integers $n_x$ and conversely \item[(ii)] every $x \in G$ has the form $\sum_i m_i u_i$ with integers $m_i$. \end{itemize}

---

\label{7.3}
The set of all products $v = v_1 v_2 \ldots v_M,$ in which each $v_i$ has one of the forms $u_i^{r_i}$ $(r_i \geq 0)$ or else $(u_i^{n}x_i^{-s_i})$ $(s_i > 0),$ is an integral basis of $\mathbb{K}G.$
